  "text": "Firefox content process lifecycle management in the Fission multi-process architecture is orchestrated through several key classes in the dom/ipc/ directory:\n\n1. **ContentParent** (dom/ipc/ContentParent.h and dom/ipc/ContentParent.cpp) - The parent-side manager for content processes. ContentParent is the primary interface that handles creation, communication, and lifecycle management of content processes. It inherits from PContentParent and manages all IPC communication with child content processes.\n\n2. **ContentProcessManager** (dom/ipc/ContentProcessManager.h and dom/ipc/ContentProcessManager.cpp) - A registry and singleton that maintains all active content processes. It provides methods to add, remove, and retrieve content processes by ID (ContentParentId), as well as to register and unregister remote frames (BrowserParent). This acts as the central repository for tracking all active processes.\n\n3. **BrowserParent** (dom/ipc/BrowserParent.h) - The parent-side tab representation. BrowserParent inherits from PBrowserParent and represents a tab or frame running in a content process. It handles tab-specific communications and lifecycle events.\n\n4. **PreallocatedProcessManager** (dom/ipc/PreallocatedProcessManager.h and dom/ipc/PreallocatedProcessManager.cpp) - Manages the process preallocation pool. This class maintains a pre-started ContentParent that is ready for use, improving performance by having a process ready before it's needed. It watches preferences to enable/disable preallocation and manages the lifecycle of preallocated processes.\n\nThese components work together to provide Firefox's multi-process isolation through the Fission architecture, managing process creation via ContentParent, tracking active processes through ContentProcessManager, representing tabs through BrowserParent, and optimizing startup performance through PreallocatedProcessManager."
}

